        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spectral Setup: Baseband-1 is set for o-H2D+ 1(1,0)-1(1,1) (372.42
GHz) with bandwidth 117 MHz (94 km/s) and resolution 0.057
km/s. Baseband-2 is set for N2H+(4-3) at 372.67 GHz with bandwidth 117
MHz (94 km/s) and resolution 0.057 km/s. Baseband-3 is set for
DCO+(5-4) (360.17 GHz) with bandwidth 117 MHz (94 km/s) and resolution
0.059 km/s. Baseband-4 is set for an observation of the continuum.
The total data rate is below 12 MB/s.

Field Setup: Since the 16.6" primary beam at this frequency cannot cover
both C1-N and C1-S completely, we decide to utilize two pointings.
This way we can share calibration because the two cores are close enough.

Sensitivity Estimation: We aim for 10 times better sensitivity as our
JCMT observations. We ask for an o-H2D+ 1(1,0)-1(1,1) line sensitivity
of ~5 mK over a 0.2 km/s velocity interval over a beam of 6". The
largest beam size is only ~1", so, if necessary, we will smooth to 6"
angular resolution, which is enough for our science goal of
constraining global astrochemical models of the cores (which can still
include an assumed density structure). Since OT only allows desired
angular resolution as big as 2", we input a larger noise level to
account for the spatial smoothing. We first calculate the single
pointing on-source time in the sensitivity calculator with 5 mK, 0.2 km/s,
and 6" beam (this is allowed in sensitivity calculator). Then we input
a noise level in OT with 0.2 km/s channel width and 2" beam size to
match this on-source time. So our final input is 46 mK
sensitivity. Then the total project time is 1.05 h. (overhead is below 30%
of total time).

Miscellaneous: We use the system-defined calibration, and have no
special requirements for bandpass accuracy, scheduling time,
continuous target observations, etc.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
