    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Astrochemistry can provide important constraints on the timescale of
core formation and evolution, which can help resolve debates about
whether star formation is a fast or slow process. With this goal in
mind, we are modeling the deuteration chemistry relevant to starless
cores to predict the time evolution of the relative abundances of N2D+
and N2H+, which is observable. Focussing on two massive, apparently
starless, highly-deuterated cores we detected with ALMA in Cycle 0,
here we propose to measure ortho-H2D+ abundances in these cores,
following up on a tentative detection we made with the JCMT. The
abundance of this species is an important constraint on the models,
especially since they are sensitive to the ortho to para ratio of H2.
</prp:abstract>
